  "reading_greek": "THE TENS\n10 - Δέκα (Deka)\n20 - Είκοσι (Eikosi)\n30 - Τριάντα (Trianta)\n40 - Σαράντα (Saranta)\n50 - Πενήντα (Peninta)\n60 - Εξήντα (Exinta)\n70 - Εβδομήντα (Evdominta)\n80 - Ογδόντα (Ogdominta)\n90 - Ενενήντα (Eneninta)\n100 - Εκατό (Ekato)\n\nMONEY & QUANTITY\n- Ένα ευρώ (1 Euro)\n- Δύο ευρώ (2 Euros - Invariable!)\n- Πενήντα λεπτά (50 cents)\n- Τέσσερις γυναίκες (4 women - Fem)\n- Τρεις άνθρωποι (3 people - Masc)",
  "reading_english": "GRAMMAR: NUMBERS [(See Page 82)](/assets/grammar.pdf#page=82)\n\n1. 1, 3, 4 CHANGE GENDER:\n   - 1: Enas (M), Mia (F), Ena (N).\n   - 3: Treis (M/F), Tria (N).\n   - 4: Tessereis (M/F), Tessera (N).\n\n2. COMPOUND NUMBERS:\n   - 21 = Eikosi ena.\n   - 35 = Trianta pente.\n   - No 'and' in between. Just say the ten and the unit.\n\n3. EURO:\n   - The word 'Evro' is invariable. It does not change in plural. \n   - 'Dyo Evro', not 'Dyo Evra'.",
  "audio_script": "Let's count money. \n\nThe tens are easy once you learn them. \nTrianta (30), Saranta (40), Peninta (50)... notice the '-nta' ending.\n\nImportant: The numbers 1, 3, and 4 change gender!\n- 1: Ena (Neut) vs Enas (Masc).\n- 3: Tria (Neut) vs Treis (Masc/Fem).\n- 4: Tessera (Neut) vs Tessereis (Masc/Fem).\n\nNormally for money (Euro), we use Neuter forms. \n'Tria Evro'. 'Tessera Evro'.\n\nBut if you count people... 'Treis anthropoi' (3 people). 'Tessereis gynaikes' (4 women).\n\nAnd 'Evro' never changes. Don't add an 's'!",
